const CHEMISTRY_EDEXCEL_PRACTICE = {
  'T1': {
    name: 'Atomic Structure, Bonding and Energetics',
    questions: [
      { q: 'State the number of protons, neutrons, and electrons in an atom of potassium-39.', marks: 1, markScheme: '19 protons, 20 neutrons, 19 electrons (1 mark for all three correct).' },
      { q: 'Write the electron configuration of a chlorine atom using sub-shell notation.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1s2 2s2 2p6 3s2 3p5 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define the term "isotope".', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Atoms of the same element with the same number of protons but different numbers of neutrons (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why neon has a higher first ionisation energy than sodium.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Neon has more protons/higher nuclear charge than sodium but the same number of electron shells/similar shielding (1 mark). The outer electron in neon is held more tightly/closer to the nucleus (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the bonding in a molecule of carbon dioxide. State its shape and bond angle.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Two C=O double bonds (two pairs of shared electrons per bond) (1 mark). Linear shape (1 mark). Bond angle of 180 degrees (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Draw a dot-and-cross diagram for magnesium oxide. Show the charges on the ions.', marks: 2, diagram: true, markScheme: 'Diagram showing Mg2+ with electron configuration [2,8] and O2- with [2,8], showing the transfer of 2 electrons from Mg to O (1 mark). Correct charges shown: Mg2+ and O2- (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain, in terms of bonding, why sodium chloride conducts electricity when molten but not when solid.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'When solid, the ions are held in fixed positions in the lattice and cannot move (1 mark). When molten, the ions are free to move and carry charge (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State and explain the shape of a BF3 molecule.', marks: 2, diagram: true, markScheme: 'Trigonal planar (1 mark). Three bonding pairs of electrons repel equally and arrange themselves as far apart as possible at 120 degrees, with no lone pairs on the central atom (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why water has a higher boiling point than hydrogen sulfide.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Water has hydrogen bonding between molecules due to the O-H bond being highly polar (1 mark). The lone pairs on oxygen interact with the delta+ hydrogen of adjacent molecules (1 mark). H2S only has weaker van der Waals/London forces and permanent dipole-dipole forces as S is less electronegative than O, so hydrogen bonding does not occur (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the enthalpy change for the reaction: CH4 + 2O2 -> CO2 + 2H2O, using the following mean bond enthalpies: C-H = 412, O=O = 496, C=O = 743, O-H = 463 kJ/mol.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Bonds broken: 4(C-H) + 2(O=O) = 4(412) + 2(496) = 1648 + 992 = 2640 kJ (1 mark). Bonds formed: 2(C=O) + 4(O-H) = 2(743) + 4(463) = 1486 + 1852 = 3338 kJ (1 mark). Delta H = 2640 - 3338 = -698 kJ/mol (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by a "dative covalent bond" and give one example.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A dative (coordinate) covalent bond is formed when one atom provides both electrons in the shared pair (1 mark). Example: NH4+ ion (the bond between N and the fourth H) or CO or [Al(OH)4]- (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State what is meant by the term "mean bond enthalpy".', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The average energy required to break one mole of a particular type of covalent bond (1 mark) in the gaseous state, averaged across a range of different compounds (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the second ionisation energy of sodium is much larger than the first.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The second electron is removed from a full inner shell (2p6) which is closer to the nucleus and has less shielding (1 mark). This electron experiences a much greater effective nuclear charge so much more energy is needed to remove it (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State and explain the trend in electronegativity across Period 3.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Electronegativity increases across Period 3 from Na to Cl (1 mark). Nuclear charge increases while atomic radius decreases, so the bonding electrons are attracted more strongly (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A sample of boron consists of 20% boron-10 and 80% boron-11. Calculate the relative atomic mass.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Ar = (0.20 x 10) + (0.80 x 11) = 2.0 + 8.8 (1 mark) = 10.8 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the enthalpy of atomisation of chlorine (Cl2) is half the Cl-Cl bond enthalpy.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Enthalpy of atomisation is the energy change when 1 mole of gaseous atoms is formed from the element in its standard state (1 mark). Breaking 1 mole of Cl2 produces 2 moles of Cl atoms, so atomisation (forming 1 mole) is half the bond enthalpy (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Compare the structures of diamond and graphite, explaining why graphite is used as a lubricant.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Diamond: each C bonded to 4 others in a rigid tetrahedral structure (1 mark). Graphite: each C bonded to 3 others in layers with delocalised electrons between layers (1 mark). The layers in graphite are held together by weak London forces and can slide over each other, making it a good lubricant (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define "enthalpy of formation" and write the equation representing the standard enthalpy of formation of ethanol.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The enthalpy change when 1 mole of a compound is formed from its elements in their standard states under standard conditions (1 mark). 2C(s) + 3H2(g) + 1/2 O2(g) -> C2H5OH(l) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why metallic bonding leads to high electrical conductivity in metals.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Metallic bonding involves a lattice of positive metal ions surrounded by a sea of delocalised electrons (1 mark). These delocalised electrons are free to move through the structure when a potential difference is applied, carrying charge (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Using successive ionisation energy data (577, 1817, 2745, 11578 kJ/mol), determine which group the element belongs to.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'There is a large jump between the 3rd and 4th ionisation energies (1 mark). This indicates 3 electrons in the outer shell, so the element is in Group 3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State and explain the shape of the ammonium ion, NH4+.', marks: 2, diagram: true, markScheme: 'Tetrahedral shape with bond angles of 109.5 degrees (1 mark). Four bonding pairs of electrons around the central nitrogen repel equally (one being a dative bond from N to H+), with no lone pairs (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define "electron affinity" and state whether the first electron affinity of chlorine is exothermic or endothermic.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'First electron affinity is the enthalpy change when 1 electron is added to each atom in 1 mole of gaseous atoms to form 1 mole of gaseous 1- ions (1 mark). The first electron affinity of chlorine is exothermic (negative) because energy is released when the electron is attracted into the outer shell (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the boiling points of the noble gases increase from He to Xe.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Noble gases have only London dispersion forces between atoms (1 mark). As atomic number increases, the number of electrons increases, so the electron cloud is larger and more polarisable, leading to stronger London forces and higher boiling points (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State Hess\'s law.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'The total enthalpy change for a reaction is independent of the route taken, provided the initial and final conditions are the same (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Using Hess\'s law and enthalpies of combustion, calculate the enthalpy of formation of methane given: C(s) = -393, H2(g) = -286, CH4(g) = -890 kJ/mol.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'By Hess\'s law: deltaHf(CH4) = sum of combustion of elements - combustion of CH4 (1 mark). deltaHf = [(-393) + 2(-286)] - (-890) (1 mark). = -393 - 572 + 890 = -75 kJ/mol (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why phosphorus can form PCl5 but nitrogen cannot form NCl5.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Phosphorus has available 3d orbitals which can accommodate extra electrons, allowing an expanded octet with 5 bonding pairs (1 mark). Nitrogen is in Period 2 and has no available d orbitals, so it cannot exceed an octet of electrons (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A mass spectrum of a sample of chlorine shows peaks at m/z = 35, 37, 70, 72, and 74. Explain the origin of each peak.', marks: 3, markScheme: '35 and 37 are the Cl-35+ and Cl-37+ isotope ions (1 mark). 70 is 35Cl-35Cl+, 72 is 35Cl-37Cl+, and 74 is 37Cl-37Cl+ molecular ions of Cl2 (1 mark). The relative heights reflect the natural abundance of the isotopes (75% Cl-35 and 25% Cl-37) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why ice is less dense than liquid water.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'In ice, hydrogen bonds hold water molecules in a regular open lattice/cage structure with large spaces between molecules (1 mark). When ice melts, some hydrogen bonds break, the lattice collapses, and molecules move closer together on average, increasing density (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the trend in atomic radius down Group 1 and explain the reason.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Atomic radius increases down Group 1 (1 mark). Each element has an additional electron shell/energy level, so the outer electron is further from the nucleus despite increasing nuclear charge (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by a "polar covalent bond" and give one example of a molecule containing one.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A polar covalent bond is a covalent bond where electrons are unequally shared between atoms of different electronegativities, creating partial charges (delta+ and delta-) (1 mark). Example: H-Cl, where Cl is more electronegative than H (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the energy change when 2 moles of water are formed from gaseous atoms: 2H(g) + O(g) -> H2O(g), given O-H bond enthalpy = 463 kJ/mol.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Each water molecule has 2 O-H bonds, so energy released forming 1 mole = 2 x 463 = 926 kJ (1 mark). For 2 moles: 2 x 926 = 1852 kJ released (delta H = -1852 kJ) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why beryllium has a higher ionisation energy than boron, which seems to contradict the general trend across Period 2.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Beryllium has the configuration 1s2 2s2 with a full 2s sub-shell, which is relatively stable (1 mark). Boron has 1s2 2s2 2p1 and the 2p electron is in a higher energy sub-shell, further from the nucleus and easier to remove despite the extra proton (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State two properties of ionic compounds and relate each to the bonding present.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'High melting point: strong electrostatic forces between oppositely charged ions require a lot of energy to overcome (1 mark). Conduct when molten/dissolved: ions are free to move and carry charge (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is the shape of a molecule of PCl3? Explain your answer.', marks: 2, diagram: true, markScheme: 'Trigonal pyramidal (1 mark). Phosphorus has 3 bonding pairs and 1 lone pair; lone pair-bonding pair repulsion is greater than bonding pair-bonding pair repulsion, compressing the bond angles to about 107 degrees (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between intermolecular forces and intramolecular forces, giving an example of each.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Intermolecular forces are forces between molecules (e.g., hydrogen bonding in water, London forces in methane) - these are overcome during boiling (1 mark). Intramolecular forces are bonds within a molecule (e.g., the O-H covalent bonds in water) - these are much stronger and are not broken during changes of state (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A compound of nitrogen and hydrogen has the empirical formula NH3. Its relative molecular mass is 17. Determine its molecular formula.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Empirical formula mass of NH3 = 14 + 3(1) = 17. Since Mr = 17, the molecular formula is NH3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Draw the shapes of s and p orbitals.', marks: 2, diagram: true, markScheme: 's orbital: spherical shape around the nucleus (1 mark). p orbital: dumbbell/figure-of-eight shape with two lobes either side of the nucleus (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the number of electrons in a d sub-shell and explain why chromium has the electron configuration [Ar] 3d5 4s1 rather than [Ar] 3d4 4s2.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A d sub-shell holds a maximum of 10 electrons (1 mark). Chromium adopts [Ar] 3d5 4s1 because a half-filled d sub-shell is particularly stable due to the exchange energy associated with having 5 unpaired electrons in 5 d orbitals (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the conditions under which standard enthalpy changes are measured.', marks: 1, markScheme: '100 kPa pressure, 298 K (25 degrees C), 1 mol dm-3 concentration for solutions, substances in standard states (1 mark for at least two conditions).' },
      { q: 'Explain why van der Waals forces exist even in non-polar molecules.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Electrons in any atom or molecule are constantly moving, creating temporary/instantaneous dipoles (1 mark). These temporary dipoles induce dipoles in neighbouring molecules, causing a weak attraction (London dispersion force) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why covalent bonds are directional but ionic bonds are not.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Covalent bonds involve sharing of electron pairs between specific atoms, so the bond exists in a particular direction between those atoms (1 mark). Ionic bonds are electrostatic attractions between oppositely charged ions which are non-directional: each ion attracts all surrounding ions of opposite charge equally in all directions (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe how a mass spectrometer works, stating the four main stages.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Ionisation: sample is vaporised and bombarded with high-energy electrons to form positive ions (1 mark). Acceleration: positive ions are accelerated by an electric field (1 mark). Deflection: ions are deflected by a magnetic field; lighter ions and more highly charged ions are deflected more (1 mark). Detection: ions reach the detector which measures their abundance; a mass spectrum is produced showing m/z values (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the percentage by mass of oxygen in calcium carbonate, CaCO3.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Mr of CaCO3 = 40 + 12 + 3(16) = 100 (1 mark). Percentage O = (48/100) x 100 = 48% (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State what is meant by a covalent bond.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'A shared pair of electrons between two atoms, where both atoms contribute one electron to the shared pair (or a dative bond where one atom contributes both) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why sulfur hexafluoride (SF6) is non-polar despite containing polar S-F bonds.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'SF6 has an octahedral shape with 6 S-F bonds arranged symmetrically (1 mark). The individual bond dipoles cancel out due to the symmetrical arrangement, giving no overall molecular dipole (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the main assumptions of the ideal gas model and relate them to the ideal gas equation PV = nRT.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Molecules have negligible volume compared to the volume of the container (1 mark). There are no intermolecular forces between molecules (1 mark). Collisions between molecules are perfectly elastic and the equation relates pressure, volume, amount, and temperature, applying best at high temperatures and low pressures (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the enthalpy change of the reaction C2H4(g) + H2(g) -> C2H6(g) using enthalpies of combustion: C2H4 = -1411, H2 = -286, C2H6 = -1560 kJ/mol.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Using Hess\'s law: deltaH = sum(combustion of reactants) - sum(combustion of products) (1 mark). deltaH = (-1411 + (-286)) - (-1560) (1 mark). = -1697 + 1560 = -137 kJ/mol (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why aluminium has a higher melting point than sodium in terms of metallic bonding.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Aluminium has 3 delocalised electrons per atom compared to 1 for sodium, and Al3+ is smaller than Na+ (1 mark). This gives stronger metallic bonding due to greater charge and smaller ionic radius, requiring more energy to break (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is a coordinate (dative covalent) bond? Explain how one forms in the reaction of NH3 with BF3.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A coordinate bond is a covalent bond where both electrons in the shared pair come from one atom (1 mark). NH3 has a lone pair on N which is donated into the empty p orbital on B in BF3, forming a dative bond: H3N->BF3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State three factors that affect the lattice enthalpy of an ionic compound.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The charge on the ions: higher charges give more exothermic lattice enthalpy (1 mark). The size of the ions: smaller ions give more exothermic lattice enthalpy (1 mark). The packing arrangement/crystal structure of the lattice (1 mark).' }
    ]
  },
  'T2': {
    name: 'Kinetics, Equilibrium and Redox',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define "activation energy".', marks: 1, markScheme: 'The minimum energy required for a reaction to occur/for a successful collision between particles (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Draw a labelled Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution curve for a gas at two different temperatures. Mark the activation energy.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: 'Correct shape: curve starts at origin, rises to a peak then tails off at high energy (1 mark). Second curve at higher temperature: peak lower and shifted right, with a longer tail (1 mark). Ea marked on x-axis showing a greater proportion of particles exceed Ea at higher temperature (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain how a catalyst increases the rate of a reaction.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A catalyst provides an alternative reaction pathway (1 mark) with a lower activation energy, so more particles have sufficient energy to react, increasing the frequency of successful collisions (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the expression for Kc for the reaction: 2SO2(g) + O2(g) <=> 2SO3(g).', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Kc = [SO3]^2 / ([SO2]^2[O2]) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'For the equilibrium N2O4(g) <=> 2NO2(g), delta H = +57 kJ/mol. Predict the effect on the position of equilibrium when temperature is increased.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The forward reaction is endothermic (1 mark). Increasing temperature shifts the equilibrium to the right, producing more NO2 (brown gas), to absorb the extra heat (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the oxidation state of nitrogen in: (a) NO2, (b) NH3, (c) HNO3.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(a) +4 (1 mark). (b) -3 (1 mark). (c) +5 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the ionic half-equation for the reduction of permanganate ions in acid solution.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'MnO4- + 8H+ + 5e- -> Mn2+ + 4H2O (1 mark for correct species, 1 mark for balanced charges and atoms).' },
      { q: 'Define the term "dynamic equilibrium".', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A dynamic equilibrium exists when the rate of the forward reaction equals the rate of the reverse reaction (1 mark) and the concentrations of reactants and products remain constant (macroscopic properties do not change) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'The rate equation for a reaction is rate = k[X][Y]^2. State the overall order and the units of k.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Overall order = 1 + 2 = 3 (1 mark). Units of k: mol-2 dm6 s-1 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the rate-determining step.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'The slowest step in a multi-step reaction mechanism, which controls the overall rate of the reaction (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A reaction is first order with respect to A. Sketch a graph of [A] against time and a graph of rate against [A].', marks: 2, diagram: true, markScheme: '[A] vs time: exponential decay curve with constant half-life (1 mark). Rate vs [A]: straight line through the origin showing rate is directly proportional to [A] (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why a catalyst does not change the value of Kc.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A catalyst increases the rate of both the forward and reverse reactions equally (1 mark). The position of equilibrium is unchanged, so the ratio of product to reactant concentrations remains the same (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the oxidation state of chromium in K2Cr2O7.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Let Cr = x. 2(+1) + 2x + 7(-2) = 0; 2 + 2x - 14 = 0; x = +6 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the half-equations for the electrolysis of molten sodium chloride and state what is produced at each electrode.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'At cathode (reduction): Na+ + e- -> Na; sodium metal is produced (1 mark). At anode (oxidation): 2Cl- -> Cl2 + 2e-; chlorine gas is produced (1 mark). Overall: 2NaCl -> 2Na + Cl2 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why increasing the concentration of a reactant increases the rate of reaction.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'More particles per unit volume (1 mark). More frequent collisions so more successful collisions per unit time (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'For the reaction A -> products, the half-life is constant at 30 seconds. What is the order of this reaction?', marks: 1, markScheme: 'First order (a constant half-life is characteristic of a first-order reaction) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is a disproportionation reaction? Give an example with oxidation states.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A disproportionation reaction is one where the same element is simultaneously oxidised and reduced (1 mark). Example: 2Cu+(+1) -> Cu(0) + Cu2+(+2); copper is both oxidised (+1 to +2) and reduced (+1 to 0) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State what is meant by the standard electrode potential (E°).', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The EMF of a half-cell measured relative to a standard hydrogen electrode (1 mark) under standard conditions (298 K, 100 kPa, 1 mol dm-3 solutions) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Using the Arrhenius equation, explain how a graph of ln k against 1/T can be used to find the activation energy.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The Arrhenius equation: k = Ae^(-Ea/RT); taking natural logs: ln k = ln A - Ea/RT (1 mark). A plot of ln k (y-axis) against 1/T (x-axis) gives a straight line (1 mark). The gradient = -Ea/R, so Ea = -gradient x R (where R = 8.314 J mol-1 K-1) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'For the equilibrium H2(g) + I2(g) <=> 2HI(g), explain the effect of adding an inert gas at constant volume.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Adding an inert gas at constant volume does not change the partial pressures or concentrations of the reacting gases (1 mark). Therefore there is no effect on the position of equilibrium (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the cell potential for Zn(s)|Zn2+(aq)||Cu2+(aq)|Cu(s) given E°(Zn2+/Zn) = -0.76V and E°(Cu2+/Cu) = +0.34V.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'E°cell = E°(cathode) - E°(anode) = E°(Cu2+/Cu) - E°(Zn2+/Zn) (1 mark). = +0.34 - (-0.76) = +1.10 V (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State Le Chatelier\'s principle.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'If a system at equilibrium is subjected to a change in conditions, the system will shift to oppose/counteract the change (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why increasing the pressure has no effect on the position of equilibrium for: H2(g) + Cl2(g) <=> 2HCl(g).', marks: 2, markScheme: 'There are equal numbers of moles of gas on both sides of the equation (2 moles on each side) (1 mark). Pressure changes only affect equilibria where there is a difference in total moles of gas (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A student measures the initial rate of a reaction at 25°C and 35°C. The rate approximately doubles. Explain this observation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A 10 K increase in temperature increases the proportion of particles with energy >= Ea significantly (1 mark). The Boltzmann distribution shifts so many more particles exceed the activation energy threshold, approximately doubling the rate (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define "oxidising agent" and "reducing agent" in terms of electron transfer.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'An oxidising agent is a substance that accepts/gains electrons (and is itself reduced) (1 mark). A reducing agent is a substance that donates/loses electrons (and is itself oxidised) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'In the Haber process, explain why a compromise temperature of about 450°C is used.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The reaction is exothermic so a lower temperature favours a higher yield (shifts equilibrium right) (1 mark). However, a low temperature gives a very slow rate of reaction (1 mark). 450°C is a compromise: reasonable rate with acceptable yield, used with an iron catalyst to further increase rate (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the equilibrium expression for Kp for: N2(g) + 3H2(g) <=> 2NH3(g).', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Kp = p(NH3)^2 / (p(N2) x p(H2)^3) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A reaction is zero order with respect to reactant B. Sketch the graph of [B] against time and rate against [B].', marks: 2, diagram: true, markScheme: '[B] vs time: straight line with negative gradient (linear decrease) (1 mark). Rate vs [B]: horizontal line (rate is constant regardless of [B]) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why a fuel cell is considered more efficient than a combustion engine.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A fuel cell converts chemical energy directly to electrical energy without the intermediate step of heat energy (1 mark). Less energy is wasted as heat so the overall efficiency is higher (typically 60-80% vs 20-40% for a combustion engine) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the conditions needed for a hydrogen-oxygen fuel cell to operate.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Hydrogen gas supplied to the anode and oxygen gas to the cathode (1 mark). A proton exchange membrane (PEM) or electrolyte to allow H+ ions to pass between electrodes, and an external circuit for electron flow (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'For the reaction 2NO(g) + O2(g) -> 2NO2(g), rate = k[NO]^2[O2]. Suggest a two-step mechanism consistent with this rate equation.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Step 1 (slow, rate-determining): 2NO -> N2O2 (or NO + NO -> N2O2) (1 mark). Step 2 (fast): N2O2 + O2 -> 2NO2 (1 mark). The slow step involves two molecules of NO, giving second order in NO, and O2 is not in the slow step but appears in the overall rate equation as it is involved in the fast step after the rds - the rate equation matches rate = k[NO]^2 with implicit dependence on O2 from the rds molecularity (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the "mole fraction" of a gas in a mixture.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'The mole fraction is the number of moles of a particular gas divided by the total number of moles of all gases in the mixture (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'The partial pressure of nitrogen in a gas mixture is 60 kPa and total pressure is 200 kPa. Calculate the mole fraction of nitrogen.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Mole fraction = p(N2)/p(total) = 60/200 = 0.3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A galvanic cell has E°cell = +0.46V. Calculate delta G given n = 2 and F = 96500 C/mol.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'deltaG = -nFE°cell = -(2)(96500)(0.46) (1 mark). = -88780 J/mol = -88.8 kJ/mol (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the reaction between zinc and copper sulfate is feasible but the reverse reaction is not, using standard electrode potentials.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'E°cell for Zn + Cu2+ is positive (+1.10V), meaning deltaG is negative, so the reaction is thermodynamically feasible (1 mark). The reverse (Cu + Zn2+) would have E°cell = -1.10V (negative), meaning deltaG is positive and the reaction is not feasible (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State what happens to the rate constant k when a catalyst is added.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'The rate constant k increases because the activation energy is lowered (according to the Arrhenius equation, lower Ea gives larger k) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'In a clock reaction, the time taken for a colour change decreases when temperature increases. Explain why.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Higher temperature means particles have more kinetic energy (1 mark). A greater proportion of collisions have energy >= Ea, so the reaction producing the colour change happens faster, reducing the time (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the overall equation for a hydrogen fuel cell operating in acidic conditions.', marks: 1, markScheme: '2H2(g) + O2(g) -> 2H2O(l) (1 mark for balanced equation).' },
      { q: 'Explain why adding more solid CaCO3 to the equilibrium CaCO3(s) <=> CaO(s) + CO2(g) does not change the position of equilibrium.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Solids do not appear in the equilibrium expression as their concentration is effectively constant (1 mark). Adding more solid does not change the concentrations in the Kc/Kp expression so the position of equilibrium is unchanged (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A second-order reaction has rate = k[A]^2. When [A] = 0.2 mol dm-3, rate = 4.0 x 10-3 mol dm-3 s-1. Calculate k.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'k = rate / [A]^2 = 4.0 x 10-3 / (0.2)^2 = 4.0 x 10-3 / 0.04 (1 mark). k = 0.1 mol-1 dm3 s-1 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State two advantages of hydrogen fuel cells over fossil fuel combustion.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The only product is water, so no CO2, NOx, or SO2 emissions/pollutants (1 mark). Higher energy efficiency as chemical energy is converted directly to electrical energy (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between homogeneous and heterogeneous catalysis, giving one example of each.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Homogeneous: catalyst is in the same phase as reactants (1 mark). Example: H+ ions catalysing ester hydrolysis, or Fe2+ in the reaction between S2O8^2- and I- (1 mark). Heterogeneous: catalyst is in a different phase from reactants (1 mark). Example: iron catalyst in the Haber process, or Pt/Pd in catalytic converters (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'For the equilibrium PCl5(g) <=> PCl3(g) + Cl2(g), the reaction is endothermic. State and explain the effect of (a) increasing temperature, (b) increasing pressure on the yield of PCl3.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(a) Increasing temperature shifts equilibrium right (endothermic direction) (1 mark), increasing the yield of PCl3 (1 mark). (b) Increasing pressure shifts equilibrium to the side with fewer moles of gas; left side has 1 mole, right has 2 moles (1 mark). So equilibrium shifts left, decreasing yield of PCl3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define "standard conditions" for electrochemistry.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Temperature 298 K, pressure 100 kPa, solution concentrations of 1.0 mol dm-3 (1 mark for at least two).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the electrode potential of a half-cell changes if the concentration of the metal ion is changed.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The electrode potential depends on the equilibrium M^n+(aq) + ne- <=> M(s) (1 mark). Changing the concentration of M^n+ shifts this equilibrium (by Le Chatelier\'s principle), changing the potential as described by the Nernst equation (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'In a reaction, the rate doubles when the concentration of reactant P doubles, but the rate is unchanged when reactant Q doubles. Write the rate equation.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'rate = k[P] (first order in P, zero order in Q) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the half-life of a first-order reaction with rate constant k = 0.0231 s-1.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'For a first-order reaction, t1/2 = ln 2 / k = 0.693 / k (1 mark). t1/2 = 0.693 / 0.0231 = 30 seconds (1 mark).' }
    ]
  },
  'T3': {
    name: 'Inorganic Chemistry',
    questions: [
      { q: 'State the flame colours of lithium, sodium, and potassium.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Lithium: red/crimson; Sodium: yellow/orange; Potassium: lilac (1 mark for all three).' },
      { q: 'Write an equation for the reaction of sodium with water and state the observations.', marks: 3, markScheme: '2Na(s) + 2H2O(l) -> 2NaOH(aq) + H2(g) (1 mark). Observations: sodium floats, melts into a ball, fizzes vigorously (1 mark). Solution becomes alkaline / universal indicator turns purple (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why fluorine is the most reactive halogen.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Fluorine has the smallest atomic radius of the halogens (1 mark). The incoming electron is added close to the nucleus with minimal shielding, so the electron is gained most easily/has the most exothermic electron affinity (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe and explain the trend in boiling points of the halogens from fluorine to iodine.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Boiling points increase from F2 to I2 (1 mark). The halogens are simple molecular substances with London dispersion forces between molecules (1 mark). As the number of electrons increases down the group, the electron clouds are larger and more polarisable, so London forces increase, requiring more energy to overcome (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the equation for the thermal decomposition of calcium carbonate and state the observation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'CaCO3(s) -> CaO(s) + CO2(g) (1 mark). White calcium carbonate decomposes on strong heating to form white calcium oxide; the gas produced turns limewater milky (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why barium hydroxide is more soluble in water than magnesium hydroxide.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The solubility of Group 2 hydroxides increases down the group (1 mark). The lattice enthalpy decreases more rapidly than the hydration enthalpy as ion size increases, making dissolution more energetically favourable for larger cations like Ba2+ (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the test for chloride, bromide, and iodide ions using silver nitrate solution.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Add dilute nitric acid (to remove carbonates/interfering ions) then silver nitrate solution (1 mark). Chloride: white precipitate (AgCl) soluble in dilute ammonia (1 mark). Bromide: cream precipitate (AgBr) soluble in concentrated ammonia. Iodide: yellow precipitate (AgI) insoluble in ammonia (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is meant by a "transition metal"? Explain why zinc is not classified as a transition metal.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A transition metal is a d-block element that forms at least one stable ion with an incomplete d sub-shell (1 mark). Zinc forms only Zn2+ which has a d10 configuration (full d shell), so it does not meet the definition (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State two uses of transition metals or their compounds as catalysts.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Iron in the Haber process for ammonia synthesis (1 mark). Vanadium(V) oxide (V2O5) in the Contact process for sulfuric acid / Pt/Pd/Rh in catalytic converters / Ni in hydrogenation of alkenes (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe what happens when sodium hydroxide solution is added dropwise to copper(II) sulfate solution.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A blue precipitate of copper(II) hydroxide forms: Cu2+(aq) + 2OH-(aq) -> Cu(OH)2(s) (1 mark). The precipitate is insoluble in excess NaOH (unlike aluminium hydroxide which would dissolve) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by "periodicity" in chemistry.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Periodicity is the recurring pattern/trend in physical and chemical properties of elements across periods of the periodic table (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State and explain the trend in atomic radius across Period 3.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Atomic radius decreases across Period 3 from Na to Cl (1 mark). Nuclear charge increases but electrons are added to the same shell with similar shielding, so electrons are pulled closer to the nucleus (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the reaction of chlorine with cold dilute sodium hydroxide and give the oxidation state changes.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Cl2 + 2NaOH -> NaCl + NaClO + H2O (1 mark). Chlorine is disproportionated: Cl(0) is reduced to Cl(-1) in NaCl (1 mark) and oxidised to Cl(+1) in NaClO (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State why sodium chloride solution is electrolysed rather than molten sodium chloride in industry, and name the products.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Electrolysis of brine (concentrated NaCl solution) is cheaper as it avoids the high energy cost of melting NaCl (mp 801 degrees C) (1 mark). Products: chlorine gas at the anode, hydrogen gas at the cathode, sodium hydroxide solution remains (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why aluminium oxide is described as amphoteric.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Amphoteric means it reacts with both acids and bases (1 mark). With acids: Al2O3 + 6HCl -> 2AlCl3 + 3H2O (1 mark). With bases: Al2O3 + 2NaOH + 3H2O -> 2NaAl(OH)4 or Al2O3 + 2NaOH -> 2NaAlO2 + H2O (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the colours of the following ions in aqueous solution: Fe2+, Fe3+, Cu2+, Cr3+.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Fe2+: pale green; Fe3+: yellow/brown (1 mark). Cu2+: blue; Cr3+: green (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by a "ligand" and give two examples of different types of ligand.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A ligand is a species (molecule or ion) that has a lone pair of electrons which it can donate to a central metal ion to form a dative/coordinate bond (1 mark). Examples: H2O (neutral ligand), Cl- (anionic ligand), NH3 (neutral), CN- (anionic) (1 mark for two different examples).' },
      { q: 'Explain why silicon dioxide has a very high melting point.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'SiO2 has a giant covalent structure (macromolecular) where each Si is bonded to 4 O atoms and each O is bonded to 2 Si atoms in a 3D network (1 mark). Many strong Si-O covalent bonds must be broken to melt it, requiring a large amount of energy (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the equation for the reaction of magnesium with dilute hydrochloric acid and describe the observations.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Mg(s) + 2HCl(aq) -> MgCl2(aq) + H2(g) (1 mark). The magnesium dissolves/disappears, effervescence/bubbles observed (hydrogen gas), solution warms up (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why transition metals can have variable oxidation states.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Transition metals have electrons in both the 3d and 4s sub-shells (1 mark). The 3d and 4s energy levels are very close in energy, so different numbers of electrons can be lost/involved in bonding, giving access to multiple oxidation states (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the colours of the precipitates formed when NaOH is added to solutions containing: Fe2+, Fe3+, Cu2+.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Fe2+: green precipitate (Fe(OH)2) which turns brown on standing in air (1 mark). Fe3+: brown/rust precipitate (Fe(OH)3). Cu2+: blue precipitate (Cu(OH)2) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the trend in the pH of Period 3 oxides dissolved in water.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Na2O and MgO dissolve to give alkaline solutions (pH 12-14 and 9-10 respectively) as they form hydroxides (1 mark). Al2O3 and SiO2 are insoluble in water (1 mark). P4O10, SO2/SO3, Cl2O7 dissolve to give acidic solutions (pH 0-3) as they form acids (H3PO4, H2SO4, HClO4) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the equation for the reaction of barium chloride with sodium sulfate and state the observation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'BaCl2(aq) + Na2SO4(aq) -> BaSO4(s) + 2NaCl(aq) (1 mark). A white precipitate of barium sulfate forms (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why chlorine can act as both an oxidising agent and a reducing agent (disproportionation) when added to water.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Cl2 + H2O -> HCl + HClO (1 mark). In this reaction, one Cl atom is reduced from 0 to -1 (in HCl, acting as oxidising agent) and the other is oxidised from 0 to +1 (in HClO, acting as reducing agent) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State why Group 1 metals are stored under oil.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'They are very reactive and would react with oxygen and/or moisture in the air, so they are stored under oil to prevent contact with air and water (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the first ionisation energy of magnesium is higher than that of aluminium.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Magnesium: 1s2 2s2 2p6 3s2 - the outer electron is in the 3s sub-shell. Aluminium: 1s2 2s2 2p6 3s2 3p1 - the outer electron is in the 3p sub-shell (1 mark). The 3p electron is higher in energy and slightly further from the nucleus than 3s, so it is easier to remove despite Al having one more proton (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is a complex ion? State the coordination number in [Fe(H2O)6]3+.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A complex ion consists of a central metal ion surrounded by ligands (molecules or ions that donate lone pairs) (1 mark). Coordination number = 6 (six water molecules each form one dative bond to Fe3+) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why Group 2 sulfates become less soluble going down the group.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The hydration enthalpy and lattice enthalpy both decrease down the group as ionic radius increases (1 mark). For sulfates, the lattice enthalpy decreases less rapidly than the hydration enthalpy, so the enthalpy of solution becomes more endothermic, decreasing solubility (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the ionic equation for the reaction between chlorine water and potassium iodide solution, and describe the colour change.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Cl2(aq) + 2I-(aq) -> 2Cl-(aq) + I2(aq) (1 mark). The solution turns brown/yellow due to the formation of iodine (from colourless KI solution) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of V2O5 as a catalyst in the Contact process.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'V2O5 catalyses the oxidation of SO2 to SO3: 2SO2 + O2 -> 2SO3 (1 mark). It works by changing oxidation state: V2O5 oxidises SO2 to SO3, being reduced to V2O4 (V goes from +5 to +4) (1 mark). V2O4 is then re-oxidised back to V2O5 by O2, completing the catalytic cycle (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State two reasons why transition metal compounds are often coloured.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Transition metal ions have partially filled d orbitals (1 mark). Ligands cause d-orbital splitting; electrons can absorb visible light and be promoted between the split d energy levels (d-d transitions), and the complementary colour is observed (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the ligand substitution reaction that occurs when excess concentrated hydrochloric acid is added to [Cu(H2O)6]2+ solution.', marks: 3, markScheme: '[Cu(H2O)6]2+ + 4Cl- -> [CuCl4]2- + 6H2O (1 mark). The solution changes from blue to yellow/green (1 mark). The coordination number changes from 6 to 4 because Cl- is a larger ligand than H2O (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State and explain why the melting points of Period 3 elements show a general trend from Na to Si and then a sharp drop.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Na, Mg, Al are metals with metallic bonding that gets stronger (more delocalised electrons, smaller ions) so melting points increase Na < Mg < Al (1 mark). Si has a giant covalent structure with very strong Si-Si bonds, giving the highest melting point in Period 3 (1 mark). P4, S8, Cl2, Ar are simple molecular with only weak London forces between molecules, so their melting points are very low (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the equation for the reaction of calcium with water and state the pH of the resulting solution.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Ca(s) + 2H2O(l) -> Ca(OH)2(aq) + H2(g) (1 mark). The solution is alkaline with a pH of approximately 12-13 (calcium hydroxide is a strong base, though sparingly soluble) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why NaCl has a higher melting point than NaBr.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Both are ionic compounds, but Cl- is smaller than Br- (1 mark). The smaller Cl- ion means the Na+ and Cl- ions are closer together, giving stronger electrostatic attraction and a higher lattice enthalpy, so more energy is needed to break the lattice (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State two uses of chlorine or its compounds in water treatment.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Chlorine/chlorine compounds are used to kill bacteria and other pathogens in drinking water (disinfection) (1 mark). Sodium hypochlorite (bleach) from the reaction of chlorine with NaOH is used in water purification and swimming pools (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why phosphorus(V) oxide (P4O10) produces an acidic solution when dissolved in water.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'P4O10 reacts with water to form phosphoric acid: P4O10 + 6H2O -> 4H3PO4 (1 mark). Phosphoric acid is an acid that dissociates to release H+ ions, lowering the pH (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A student adds ammonia solution dropwise to a solution of copper(II) sulfate. Describe the observations at each stage.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Initially: a pale blue precipitate of Cu(OH)2 forms when a small amount of NH3 is added (1 mark). On adding excess ammonia: the precipitate dissolves (1 mark) to form a deep blue solution of [Cu(NH3)4(H2O)2]2+ (the tetraamminecopper(II) ion) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the electron configuration of Fe3+ and explain why it is more stable than Fe2+.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Fe3+ = [Ar] 3d5 (1 mark). The 3d5 half-filled d sub-shell is particularly stable due to the exchange energy of 5 unpaired electrons, making Fe3+ relatively stable (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the ionic radius of Na+ is smaller than the atomic radius of Na.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Na+ has lost its outer electron, so it has one fewer electron shell (2 shells instead of 3) (1 mark). The remaining electrons are pulled closer to the nucleus by the 11 protons (same nuclear charge but fewer electrons), resulting in a smaller radius (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the equation for the reaction of sulfur dioxide with water and state the environmental problem this causes.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'SO2(g) + H2O(l) -> H2SO3(aq) (sulfurous acid) or further oxidation gives SO3 + H2O -> H2SO4 (1 mark). This causes acid rain which damages buildings (limestone), harms aquatic life, and affects plant growth (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what happens when sodium is cut with a knife, in terms of its bonding and structure.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Sodium is a soft metal because it has metallic bonding with only one delocalised electron per atom, giving relatively weak metallic bonds (1 mark). The layers of ions can slide over each other easily when force is applied, so it can be cut with a knife (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the trend in the pH of Group 1 element hydroxides.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'All Group 1 hydroxides are strong bases that fully dissociate, giving pH approximately 13-14; the pH does not significantly change down the group as they are all fully dissociated (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the electron configuration of a Cr3+ ion.', marks: 1, markScheme: '[Ar] 3d3 (electrons removed from 4s first, then 3d: Cr is [Ar] 3d5 4s1, losing 3 electrons gives [Ar] 3d3) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why transition metal complexes can show different colours depending on the ligand.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Different ligands cause different degrees of d-orbital splitting (1 mark). This changes the energy/frequency of light absorbed during d-d transitions, resulting in different complementary colours being observed (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A student adds excess NaOH to aluminium chloride solution. Write the equation and describe the observations.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Initially: AlCl3 + 3NaOH -> Al(OH)3 + 3NaCl; a white gelatinous precipitate of Al(OH)3 forms (1 mark). With excess NaOH: Al(OH)3 + NaOH -> NaAl(OH)4; the precipitate dissolves (1 mark). This is because Al(OH)3 is amphoteric and reacts with excess base to form the soluble aluminate ion [Al(OH)4]- (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the shape of [CuCl4]2- and explain why it is different from [Cu(H2O)6]2+.', marks: 2, diagram: true, markScheme: '[CuCl4]2- is tetrahedral (1 mark). Cl- ligands are larger than H2O molecules, so only 4 can fit around the central Cu2+ ion rather than 6, changing the coordination number from 6 to 4 and the geometry from octahedral to tetrahedral (1 mark).' }
    ]
  },
  'T4': {
    name: 'Organic Chemistry I',
    questions: [
      { q: 'State the general formula of an alkene and draw the structural formula of propene.', marks: 1, diagram: true, markScheme: 'CnH2n; propene: CH3CH=CH2 or CH2=CHCH3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is meant by "homologous series"? State two characteristics.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A homologous series is a family of organic compounds with the same general formula and similar chemical properties (1 mark). Members differ by CH2, show a gradual trend in physical properties, and have the same functional group (1 mark for two characteristics).' },
      { q: 'Describe how ethanol is produced from ethene by hydration. State the conditions.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Ethene reacts with steam (H2O) in the presence of a phosphoric acid (H3PO4) catalyst (1 mark). Conditions: high temperature (~300 degrees C), high pressure (~60-70 atm) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define "structural isomerism" and draw two structural isomers of C4H10.', marks: 2, diagram: true, markScheme: 'Structural isomers have the same molecular formula but different structural formulae (1 mark). Butane (CH3CH2CH2CH3) and methylpropane (CH3CH(CH3)CH3 / 2-methylpropane) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why alkenes are more reactive than alkanes.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Alkenes contain a C=C double bond which includes a pi bond (1 mark). The pi bond has a high electron density which attracts electrophiles and is weaker than a sigma bond, so it breaks more readily (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the reagents and conditions for the free radical substitution of methane with chlorine.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Reagent: chlorine gas (Cl2) (1 mark). Conditions: UV light (or sunlight) to initiate the reaction by causing homolytic fission of Cl-Cl (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the three stages (initiation, propagation, termination) for the chlorination of methane.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Initiation: Cl2 -> 2Cl (UV light causes homolytic fission) (1 mark). Propagation: Cl + CH4 -> HCl + CH3; CH3 + Cl2 -> CH3Cl + Cl (1 mark). Termination: any two radicals combine, e.g., Cl + Cl -> Cl2, CH3 + CH3 -> C2H6, CH3 + Cl -> CH3Cl (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the mechanism of electrophilic addition of Br2 to ethene.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: 'As Br2 approaches the C=C, the pi electrons repel the Br-Br bonding electrons, inducing a dipole (Br delta+ Br delta-) (1 mark). The delta+ Br acts as an electrophile, attacking the C=C double bond; a C-Br bond forms and the Br-Br bond breaks heterolytically, forming a carbocation intermediate and Br- (1 mark). Br- then attacks the carbocation to form 1,2-dibromoethane (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is Markownikoff\'s rule? Apply it to the addition of HBr to propene.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Markownikoff\'s rule states that when HX adds to an unsymmetrical alkene, the hydrogen adds to the carbon with more hydrogen atoms already attached (1 mark). With propene, H adds to C1 and Br to C2, forming 2-bromopropane as the major product (because the secondary carbocation is more stable than the primary) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe how to convert ethanol to ethanoic acid using oxidation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Heat ethanol under reflux with excess acidified potassium dichromate (K2Cr2O7/H2SO4) (1 mark). The orange dichromate turns green as Cr3+ forms; ethanol is oxidised to ethanal then to ethanoic acid (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the difference between SN1 and SN2 mechanisms in terms of the number of steps and the type of halogenoalkane that favours each.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'SN2: one step (bond breaking and forming are simultaneous); favoured by primary halogenoalkanes (less steric hindrance) (1 mark). SN1: two steps (C-X bond breaks first to form carbocation, then nucleophile attacks); favoured by tertiary halogenoalkanes (stable tertiary carbocation) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Draw and name the E and Z isomers of but-2-ene.', marks: 2, diagram: true, markScheme: 'Z-but-2-ene: the two CH3 groups are on the same side of the C=C double bond (cis) (1 mark). E-but-2-ene: the two CH3 groups are on opposite sides (trans) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why halogenoalkanes undergo nucleophilic substitution.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The C-X bond is polar because halogens are more electronegative than carbon, creating a delta+ carbon (1 mark). This delta+ carbon is susceptible to attack by nucleophiles (electron-pair donors) such as OH-, NH3, or CN- (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the conditions required for the elimination of water from ethanol to form ethene.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Heat ethanol with excess concentrated sulfuric acid (or phosphoric acid) at about 170 degrees C (1 mark). Alternatively, pass ethanol vapour over heated aluminium oxide (Al2O3) catalyst (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the equation for the nucleophilic substitution of 1-bromobutane with aqueous sodium hydroxide.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'CH3CH2CH2CH2Br + NaOH -> CH3CH2CH2CH2OH + NaBr (or with OH- as ionic equation) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by a "nucleophile" and give two examples.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A nucleophile is an electron-pair donor that attacks a positively charged or electron-deficient carbon atom (1 mark). Examples: OH-, CN-, NH3, H2O (1 mark for two).' },
      { q: 'State the conditions for the reaction of a halogenoalkane with ammonia to form an amine.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Heat the halogenoalkane with excess concentrated ammonia solution (1 mark). In a sealed tube to prevent ammonia escaping, and excess ammonia to minimise further substitution (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why ethanol has a higher boiling point than ethane.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Ethanol can form hydrogen bonds between molecules due to the O-H group (1 mark). Ethane can only form weak London dispersion forces; hydrogen bonds are much stronger intermolecular forces, so more energy is needed to overcome them (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Draw the mechanism for the SN2 reaction of bromoethane with hydroxide ions.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: 'Show the OH- nucleophile approaching the delta+ carbon from the opposite side to the C-Br bond (backside attack) (1 mark). Show a transition state with partial bonds to both OH and Br, with 5 groups around carbon (1 mark). Show the product (ethanol) with Br- as the leaving group; inversion of configuration occurs (Walden inversion) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the conditions needed for the hydration of ethene to form ethanol.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Steam/water and phosphoric acid catalyst (H3PO4 on silica) (1 mark). Temperature ~300 degrees C and pressure ~60-70 atmospheres (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is the difference between cracking and fractional distillation?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Fractional distillation is a physical process that separates crude oil into fractions based on boiling point (1 mark). Cracking is a chemical process that breaks long-chain hydrocarbons into shorter, more useful molecules (alkanes and alkenes) using heat/catalyst (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the C-Cl bond is stronger than the C-Br bond.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Chlorine is smaller than bromine, so the C-Cl bond is shorter (1 mark). A shorter bond means greater overlap of orbitals and stronger attraction between the bonding electrons and the nuclei, giving a higher bond enthalpy (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Draw the displayed formula of propan-1-ol and propan-2-ol. Classify each as primary or secondary.', marks: 2, diagram: true, markScheme: 'Propan-1-ol (CH3CH2CH2OH): the OH is on the terminal carbon which is bonded to only one other C - primary alcohol (1 mark). Propan-2-ol (CH3CH(OH)CH3): the OH is on the middle carbon bonded to two other C atoms - secondary alcohol (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the observation when acidified potassium dichromate is used to oxidise a primary alcohol.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'The orange solution turns green (as Cr2O72- is reduced to Cr3+) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why tertiary alcohols cannot be oxidised by acidified dichromate.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'In a tertiary alcohol, the carbon bonded to the -OH group has no hydrogen atoms attached (1 mark). Oxidation of alcohols requires the removal of hydrogen from this carbon, which is not possible for a tertiary alcohol, so no oxidation occurs (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the equation for the complete combustion of propane.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'C3H8 + 5O2 -> 3CO2 + 4H2O (1 mark for balanced equation).' },
      { q: 'Explain why branched-chain alkanes have lower boiling points than their straight-chain isomers.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Branched-chain alkanes have a more compact/spherical shape, reducing the surface area of the molecule (1 mark). Less surface area means fewer points of contact between molecules, resulting in weaker London dispersion forces and lower boiling points (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe how the reaction of a halogenoalkane with aqueous silver nitrate can be used to compare the reactivity of chloro-, bromo-, and iodoalkanes.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Add each halogenoalkane to ethanol then add aqueous silver nitrate (1 mark). The halide ion released by hydrolysis reacts with Ag+ to form a precipitate: AgCl (white), AgBr (cream), AgI (yellow) (1 mark). The iodoalkane produces a precipitate fastest (weakest C-I bond), followed by bromoalkane, then chloroalkane (slowest due to strongest C-Cl bond) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is an electrophile? Give two examples.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'An electrophile is an electron-pair acceptor that is attracted to regions of high electron density (1 mark). Examples: NO2+, H+, Br+ (or Br2 approaching a double bond), carbocations (1 mark for two).' },
      { q: 'Explain why propene can show positional isomerism but ethene cannot.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Propene has 3 carbon atoms, so functional groups or substituents can be placed at different positions along the chain (1 mark). Ethene only has 2 carbons, so there is only one possible position for the C=C bond and any substituent placement would give the same compound (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State what is meant by a "functional group" and name the functional groups in ethanol and propanone.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A functional group is the atom or group of atoms responsible for the characteristic chemical reactions of a compound (1 mark). Ethanol: hydroxyl group (-OH); Propanone: carbonyl group (C=O, specifically a ketone group) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the conditions for the elimination reaction of 2-bromopropane to form propene.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Heat 2-bromopropane with potassium hydroxide dissolved in ethanol (ethanolic KOH) (1 mark). The ethanol solvent and the base promote elimination rather than substitution; hot conditions favour elimination (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the equation for the reaction of ethene with hydrogen bromide. Name the product.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'CH2=CH2 + HBr -> CH3CH2Br (bromoethane) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between homolytic and heterolytic bond fission.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Homolytic fission: the bond breaks so that each atom receives one electron from the bonding pair, forming two free radicals (1 mark). Heterolytic fission: the bond breaks so that one atom receives both electrons, forming a cation and an anion (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the conditions required for the catalytic hydrogenation of ethene.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Hydrogen gas (H2) with a nickel catalyst (or Pt/Pd) (1 mark). Temperature of approximately 150 degrees C and moderate pressure (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A student reacts 1-bromobutane with potassium cyanide. Name the product and the type of reaction.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Product: pentanenitrile (CH3CH2CH2CH2CN) - the carbon chain has been extended by one carbon (1 mark). This is a nucleophilic substitution reaction; CN- acts as the nucleophile (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the dehydration of butan-2-ol can produce two different alkenes.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Butan-2-ol has the -OH group on C2. When water is eliminated, hydrogen can be lost from either C1 or C3 (1 mark). Loss from C1 gives but-1-ene; loss from C3 gives but-2-ene. But-2-ene can also exist as E and Z isomers (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the industrial importance of cracking alkanes.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Cracking converts less useful long-chain alkanes (from heavy fractions) into more useful shorter alkanes (for petrol) (1 mark). It also produces alkenes which are used as feedstock for making polymers (poly(ethene), poly(propene)) and other chemicals (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what E/Z isomerism is and state the conditions needed for it to occur.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'E/Z isomerism is a type of stereoisomerism caused by restricted rotation around a C=C double bond (1 mark). It requires two different groups on each carbon of the double bond (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the product and describe the observation when ethene is reacted with bromine water.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Product: 2-bromoethanol (CH2BrCH2OH) as the major product, as water acts as a nucleophile (1 mark). Observation: the orange/brown bromine water is decolourised (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the equation for the reaction of propan-1-ol with sodium metal.', marks: 2, markScheme: '2CH3CH2CH2OH + 2Na -> 2CH3CH2CH2ONa + H2 (1 mark for correct equation). Observation: sodium dissolves, gentle effervescence as hydrogen gas is produced (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why chloroethane (C2H5Cl) has a higher boiling point than ethane (C2H6) despite having a similar molecular mass.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Chloroethane has a polar C-Cl bond creating a permanent dipole (1 mark). This gives rise to permanent dipole-dipole forces in addition to London forces, which are stronger than the London forces alone in ethane (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A primary halogenoalkane is treated with NaOH. State the conditions that favour substitution and those that favour elimination.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Substitution: aqueous NaOH, warm/reflux - water acts as solvent favouring the nucleophile pathway (1 mark). Elimination: NaOH in ethanol solution, hot/reflux - the ethanol solvent and higher temperature favour elimination (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe one environmental advantage and one environmental disadvantage of using ethanol as a fuel.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Advantage: ethanol is a renewable fuel (made from fermentation of crops) and is approximately carbon neutral as CO2 released during combustion was absorbed by plants during growth (1 mark). Disadvantage: growing crops for biofuel uses agricultural land that could be used for food, and deforestation may occur (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the displayed formula of 2-methylpropan-2-ol and explain why it is classified as a tertiary alcohol.', marks: 2, diagram: true, markScheme: '(CH3)3COH: the central carbon bearing the OH group is bonded to three other carbon atoms (three methyl groups) (1 mark). A tertiary alcohol has the hydroxyl group attached to a carbon that is bonded to three other carbon atoms (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the meaning of the term "curly arrow" in organic mechanisms.', marks: 1, diagram: true, markScheme: 'A curly arrow represents the movement of an electron pair from an electron-rich region to an electron-poor region (1 mark).' }
    ]
  },
  'T5': {
    name: 'Thermodynamics, Acids and Bases',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define "lattice enthalpy" (formation definition).', marks: 1, markScheme: 'The enthalpy change when 1 mole of an ionic compound is formed from its gaseous ions (under standard conditions) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State whether the lattice enthalpy of formation is exothermic or endothermic, and explain why.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Exothermic (negative delta H) (1 mark). Energy is released when gaseous ions come together to form a solid ionic lattice due to the strong electrostatic attraction between oppositely charged ions (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the lattice enthalpy of MgO is more exothermic than that of NaCl.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Mg2+ and O2- have higher charges (2+ and 2-) than Na+ and Cl- (1+ and 1-), giving stronger electrostatic attraction (1 mark). The ionic radii of Mg2+ and O2- are smaller than Na+ and Cl- (1 mark). Both factors (higher charge and smaller size) mean a more exothermic lattice enthalpy (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define "enthalpy of hydration".', marks: 1, markScheme: 'The enthalpy change when 1 mole of gaseous ions is dissolved in sufficient water to form an infinitely dilute solution (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the enthalpy of solution of KCl given: lattice enthalpy = +711 kJ/mol, hydration enthalpy of K+ = -322 kJ/mol, hydration enthalpy of Cl- = -363 kJ/mol.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'deltaH(solution) = -lattice enthalpy(formation) + hydration enthalpies = +711 + (-322) + (-363) (1 mark). = +711 - 685 = +26 kJ/mol (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the equation for the entropy change of the surroundings.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'deltaS(surroundings) = -deltaH/T (where T is in Kelvin) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the entropy of a gas is higher than that of a solid at the same temperature.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'In a gas, particles are far apart with rapid random motion and many possible arrangements/energy distributions (1 mark). In a solid, particles are held in fixed positions with limited movement, giving fewer possible arrangements and lower entropy (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate delta G for a reaction where delta H = -50 kJ/mol and delta S = +100 J/K/mol at 298 K.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'deltaG = deltaH - TdeltaS = -50000 - (298 x 100) = -50000 - 29800 (note: convert kJ to J or J to kJ) (1 mark). deltaG = -79800 J/mol = -79.8 kJ/mol (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the conditions under which a reaction is spontaneous at all temperatures.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'When deltaH is negative (exothermic) and deltaS is positive: deltaG = deltaH - TdeltaS will always be negative (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define a "Bronsted-Lowry acid".', marks: 1, markScheme: 'A proton (H+) donor (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the pH of a 0.05 mol dm-3 solution of HNO3.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'HNO3 is a strong acid: [H+] = 0.05 mol dm-3 (1 mark). pH = -log(0.05) = 1.30 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the pH of a 0.1 mol dm-3 solution of NaOH at 25 degrees C (Kw = 1.0 x 10-14).', marks: 3, markScheme: 'NaOH is a strong base: [OH-] = 0.1 mol dm-3 (1 mark). [H+] = Kw/[OH-] = 1.0 x 10-14 / 0.1 = 1.0 x 10-13 (1 mark). pH = -log(1.0 x 10-13) = 13 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between a strong acid and a weak acid, with examples.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A strong acid fully dissociates in water (e.g., HCl, HNO3, H2SO4) (1 mark). A weak acid partially dissociates, establishing an equilibrium (e.g., CH3COOH, H2CO3) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the Ka expression for ethanoic acid and state what a large Ka value indicates.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Ka = [CH3COO-][H+] / [CH3COOH] (1 mark). A large Ka indicates the acid is more fully dissociated / is a stronger acid (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what a buffer solution is and name two components of an acidic buffer.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A buffer solution resists changes in pH when small amounts of acid or base are added (1 mark). An acidic buffer consists of a weak acid and its conjugate base (e.g., CH3COOH and CH3COONa) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain how a buffer made from ethanoic acid and sodium ethanoate resists a decrease in pH when acid is added.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'When H+ ions are added, the ethanoate ions (CH3COO-) from the salt react with them: CH3COO- + H+ -> CH3COOH (1 mark). This removes the added H+ ions and converts them to the weak acid, preventing a significant drop in pH (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the Henderson-Hasselbalch equation for a buffer.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'pH = pKa + log([A-]/[HA]) or pH = pKa + log([salt]/[acid]) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the pH of a buffer containing 0.1 mol dm-3 CH3COOH and 0.1 mol dm-3 CH3COONa (Ka = 1.8 x 10-5).', marks: 2, markScheme: 'pH = pKa + log([salt]/[acid]) = pKa + log(0.1/0.1) = pKa + log(1) = pKa + 0 (1 mark). pKa = -log(1.8 x 10-5) = 4.74; so pH = 4.74 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State what is meant by the "ionic product of water" (Kw) and give its value at 25 degrees C.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Kw = [H+][OH-] (the product of the concentrations of H+ and OH- ions in water at equilibrium) (1 mark). At 25 degrees C, Kw = 1.0 x 10-14 mol2 dm-6 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the pH of pure water increases above 7 at temperatures below 25 degrees C.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The dissociation of water (H2O <=> H+ + OH-) is endothermic, so Kw decreases at lower temperatures (1 mark). Lower Kw means lower [H+], so pH = -log[H+] increases above 7, but the water is still neutral as [H+] = [OH-] (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Sketch a pH titration curve for the titration of a strong acid with a strong base.', marks: 2, diagram: true, markScheme: 'Curve starts at low pH (around 1), remains relatively flat, then shows a very sharp vertical rise at the equivalence point (1 mark). The equivalence point is at pH 7, and the curve levels off at high pH (around 13) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Why is phenolphthalein a suitable indicator for a weak acid-strong base titration?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The equivalence point for a weak acid-strong base titration is above pH 7 (around pH 8-10) (1 mark). Phenolphthalein changes colour between pH 8.2 and 10.0, which falls within the steep part of the titration curve at the equivalence point (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the Born-Haber cycle steps needed to calculate the lattice enthalpy of CaCl2.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: 'Atomisation of Ca: Ca(s) -> Ca(g) (1 mark). First and second ionisation of Ca: Ca(g) -> Ca2+(g) + 2e- (1 mark). Atomisation of Cl (x2): Cl2(g) -> 2Cl(g) (1 mark). Electron affinity of Cl (x2): 2Cl(g) + 2e- -> 2Cl-(g), then lattice formation: Ca2+(g) + 2Cl-(g) -> CaCl2(s) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the enthalpy of neutralisation of a weak acid by a strong base is less exothermic than that of a strong acid by a strong base.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'For a strong acid-strong base, all the energy comes from H+ + OH- -> H2O (approximately -57 kJ/mol) (1 mark). For a weak acid, some energy is used to dissociate the weak acid before neutralisation can occur (endothermic step), making the overall enthalpy change less exothermic (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A reaction has deltaH = +100 kJ/mol and deltaS = +200 J/K/mol. At what temperature does it become spontaneous?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'At the boundary, deltaG = 0: deltaH = TdeltaS, so T = deltaH/deltaS = 100000/200 (1 mark). T = 500 K; the reaction is spontaneous above 500 K (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the term "second electron affinity" and state whether it is exothermic or endothermic.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The second electron affinity is the enthalpy change when 1 electron is added to each ion in 1 mole of gaseous 1- ions to form 1 mole of gaseous 2- ions: O-(g) + e- -> O2-(g) (1 mark). It is endothermic (positive) because energy must be supplied to overcome the repulsion between the incoming electron and the already negatively charged ion (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate [H+] from a pH of 3.5.', marks: 1, markScheme: '[H+] = 10^(-pH) = 10^(-3.5) = 3.16 x 10-4 mol dm-3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why dissolving NaOH in water is highly exothermic.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The lattice enthalpy of NaOH must be overcome (endothermic) but the hydration enthalpies of Na+ and OH- are highly exothermic (1 mark). The sum of the hydration enthalpies exceeds the lattice enthalpy, so the overall enthalpy of solution is significantly negative/exothermic (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the relationship between Ka and pKa.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'pKa = -log10(Ka) (or Ka = 10^(-pKa)) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Predict the sign of deltaS for the reaction: CaCO3(s) -> CaO(s) + CO2(g).', marks: 1, markScheme: 'deltaS is positive because a gas (CO2) is produced from a solid, increasing disorder (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A 25.0 cm3 sample of 0.100 mol dm-3 HCl is titrated with 0.100 mol dm-3 NaOH. Calculate the volume of NaOH required to reach the equivalence point.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'HCl + NaOH -> NaCl + H2O (1:1 ratio). Moles HCl = 0.025 x 0.100 = 0.0025 mol. Volume NaOH = 0.0025/0.100 = 0.025 dm3 = 25.0 cm3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the theoretical and experimental lattice enthalpies for NaCl are similar, but for AgI they differ significantly.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The theoretical (Born-Lande) lattice enthalpy assumes a purely ionic model with spherical ions (1 mark). For NaCl, the ions are approximately spherical with little polarisation, so the ionic model works well and values agree closely (1 mark). For AgI, Ag+ is small with 18 electrons and polarises the large I- ion significantly, introducing covalent character; the experimental lattice enthalpy is more exothermic than the theoretical, reflecting the extra bonding (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the pH of a buffer made by mixing 50 cm3 of 0.2 mol dm-3 CH3COOH with 50 cm3 of 0.1 mol dm-3 NaOH. (Ka = 1.8 x 10-5)', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Moles CH3COOH = 0.05 x 0.2 = 0.01 mol. Moles NaOH = 0.05 x 0.1 = 0.005 mol (1 mark). NaOH neutralises some acid: CH3COOH remaining = 0.01 - 0.005 = 0.005 mol; CH3COO- formed = 0.005 mol (1 mark). [acid] = [salt] since equal moles in same total volume, so pH = pKa + log(1) = pKa (1 mark). pH = -log(1.8 x 10-5) = 4.74 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of "entropy of the surroundings" and how it relates to enthalpy change.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'When an exothermic reaction occurs, heat is transferred to the surroundings, increasing the disorder/entropy of the surroundings (1 mark). deltaS(surr) = -deltaH/T: more exothermic reactions (more negative deltaH) give a larger positive entropy change of the surroundings (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State and explain one limitation of using deltaG to predict whether a reaction will actually occur.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A negative deltaG means the reaction is thermodynamically feasible, but it says nothing about the rate/kinetics (1 mark). A reaction may have a very high activation energy barrier, making it kinetically stable even though it is thermodynamically favourable (e.g., diamond to graphite) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A student measures the pH of 0.1 mol dm-3 ethanoic acid as 2.87. Calculate the Ka value.', marks: 3, markScheme: '[H+] = 10^(-2.87) = 1.35 x 10-3 mol dm-3 (1 mark). Ka = [H+]^2/[HA] (assuming [H+] = [A-] and [HA] approx = 0.1) (1 mark). Ka = (1.35 x 10-3)^2/0.1 = 1.82 x 10-5 mol dm-3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'For H2O(l) <=> H+(aq) + OH-(aq), explain why Kw increases when temperature increases.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The dissociation of water is endothermic (deltaH positive) (1 mark). Increasing temperature shifts the equilibrium to the right (favouring the endothermic direction), producing more H+ and OH- ions, so Kw increases (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why a conjugate base is formed when an acid donates a proton.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'When an acid HA donates a proton (H+), the remaining species A- is the conjugate base because it can accept a proton to reform the acid (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State two factors that affect the magnitude of lattice enthalpy.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The charge on the ions: higher charges lead to more exothermic lattice enthalpy (1 mark). The size/radius of the ions: smaller ions lead to more exothermic lattice enthalpy due to shorter interionic distances and stronger attraction (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by "enthalpy of atomisation" of an element.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'The enthalpy change when 1 mole of gaseous atoms is formed from the element in its standard state under standard conditions (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A reaction has deltaG = 0. What does this tell us about the system?', marks: 1, markScheme: 'The system is at equilibrium; there is no net tendency for the reaction to proceed in either direction (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why adding water to a buffer solution does not significantly change the pH.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Adding water dilutes both the weak acid and its conjugate base equally (1 mark). The ratio [A-]/[HA] remains approximately the same, so pH = pKa + log([A-]/[HA]) hardly changes (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe how you would determine the Ka of a weak acid experimentally using a pH meter and titration.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Titrate the weak acid with a strong base (e.g., NaOH) while monitoring pH with a pH meter (1 mark). Identify the half-equivalence point on the titration curve (where half the acid has been neutralised) (1 mark). At the half-equivalence point, [HA] = [A-], so pH = pKa; read the pH at this point and convert: Ka = 10^(-pH) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State whether entropy increases, decreases, or stays the same for: (a) 2H2(g) + O2(g) -> 2H2O(l), (b) NH4Cl(s) -> NH3(g) + HCl(g).', marks: 2, markScheme: '(a) Entropy decreases: 3 moles of gas form 2 moles of liquid (much less disorder) (1 mark). (b) Entropy increases: 1 mole of solid forms 2 moles of gas (much more disorder) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the pH of a 0.020 mol dm-3 solution of Ba(OH)2.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Ba(OH)2 fully dissociates: [OH-] = 2 x 0.020 = 0.040 mol dm-3 (1 mark). [H+] = Kw/[OH-] = 1.0 x 10-14/0.040 = 2.5 x 10-13. pH = -log(2.5 x 10-13) = 12.6 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what happens to the feasibility of an endothermic reaction with a positive entropy change as temperature increases.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'deltaG = deltaH - TdeltaS. With positive deltaH and positive deltaS, as T increases the TdeltaS term gets larger (1 mark). At sufficiently high T, TdeltaS exceeds deltaH and deltaG becomes negative, making the reaction feasible (1 mark).' }
    ]
  },
  'T6': {
    name: 'Advanced Organic Chemistry and Analysis',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Explain why benzene undergoes electrophilic substitution rather than electrophilic addition.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Benzene has a very stable delocalised pi system (1 mark). Substitution preserves the aromatic ring and its delocalisation energy, whereas addition would break the aromaticity and lose the stabilisation energy of about 150 kJ/mol (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the reagents and conditions for the nitration of benzene.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Concentrated nitric acid and concentrated sulfuric acid (1 mark). Temperature below 55 degrees C (reflux) to avoid multiple substitutions (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the equation for the generation of the nitronium ion from mixed acids.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'HNO3 + H2SO4 -> NO2+ + HSO4- + H2O (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the reagents and catalyst for Friedel-Crafts acylation of benzene.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'An acyl chloride (e.g., CH3COCl) with a Lewis acid catalyst (AlCl3 or anhydrous aluminium chloride) (1 mark). Reflux conditions (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the test to distinguish an aldehyde from a ketone using Tollens\' reagent.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Warm the compound with Tollens\' reagent (ammoniacal silver nitrate solution/[Ag(NH3)2]+) in a water bath (1 mark). An aldehyde gives a silver mirror (Ag+ reduced to Ag); a ketone gives no reaction (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the products when ethanal is reduced with NaBH4.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Ethanol (CH3CH2OH); the aldehyde is reduced to a primary alcohol (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the nucleophilic addition mechanism for the reaction of ethanal with HCN.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: 'CN- (nucleophile, generated from HCN + base) attacks the delta+ carbon of the C=O group (1 mark). The pi bond in C=O breaks, with both electrons going to oxygen, forming an alkoxide intermediate (1 mark). The alkoxide is protonated by HCN (or water) to form the cyanohydrin product: 2-hydroxypropanenitrile for propanone or 2-hydroxyethanenitrile for ethanal (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Name the product formed when propanoyl chloride reacts with ethanol.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Ethyl propanoate (an ester) + HCl (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Name the product formed when ethanoyl chloride reacts with ammonia.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Ethanamide (CH3CONH2) + HCl (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the reagents needed to convert a carboxylic acid to an acyl chloride.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'SOCl2 (thionyl chloride) or PCl5 (phosphorus pentachloride) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is an amide bond? State the functional group present.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'An amide bond is a C(=O)-N linkage (also called a peptide bond in proteins); the functional group is -CONH- (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the repeating unit structure of a polyester formed from a diol and a dicarboxylic acid.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The repeating unit contains ester linkages (-COO-) formed between the -COOH of the acid and the -OH of the alcohol (1 mark). Water is eliminated in each condensation step (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Name the type of polymerisation that produces nylon-6,6 and state the monomers.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Condensation polymerisation (1 mark). Monomers: hexanedioic acid (adipic acid, HOOC(CH2)4COOH) and 1,6-diaminohexane (H2N(CH2)6NH2) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'In 1H NMR, what information does (a) the number of peaks, (b) the chemical shift, and (c) the integration give?', marks: 3, markScheme: '(a) Number of peaks = number of different hydrogen environments (1 mark). (b) Chemical shift indicates the type of environment/electronic surroundings of the hydrogen atoms (1 mark). (c) Integration (area under peak) gives the relative number of hydrogen atoms in each environment (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the n+1 rule in NMR and use it to predict the splitting pattern for the CH3 group in ethanol.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The n+1 rule: a peak is split into (n+1) lines where n is the number of equivalent hydrogen atoms on adjacent carbons (1 mark). The CH3 in ethanol is next to CH2 (2 H atoms), so it is split into a triplet (2+1 = 3 lines) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why TMS (tetramethylsilane) is used as a reference standard in NMR spectroscopy.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'TMS produces a single sharp peak (all 12 H atoms are equivalent) at a chemical shift of 0 ppm, well away from most other absorptions (1 mark). It is chemically inert, volatile (easy to remove), and miscible with most organic solvents (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A compound has the molecular formula C3H6O. It gives a positive 2,4-DNP test but a negative Tollens\' test. Identify the compound.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Positive 2,4-DNP confirms a carbonyl group (C=O) (1 mark). Negative Tollens\' test means it is not an aldehyde, so it must be a ketone: propanone (CH3COCH3) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'In IR spectroscopy, what absorption would you look for to identify (a) an O-H group in an alcohol and (b) a C=O group?', marks: 2, markScheme: '(a) Broad absorption around 3200-3550 cm-1 for O-H in an alcohol (1 mark). (b) Strong sharp absorption around 1680-1750 cm-1 for C=O (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is the molecular ion peak (M+) in mass spectrometry and why is it useful?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The M+ peak is caused by the intact molecule losing one electron to form a positive ion with the same mass as the molecule (1 mark). It gives the relative molecular mass of the compound directly (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A mass spectrum shows M+ at 46 and fragments at m/z = 31 and 15. Suggest the identity of the compound and explain the fragments.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'M+ = 46 suggests ethanol (C2H5OH, Mr = 46) (1 mark). m/z = 31: loss of 15 (CH3) from the molecular ion gives CHO+ or CH2OH+ (1 mark). m/z = 15: CH3+ fragment (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the difference between an addition polymer and a condensation polymer in terms of structure and formation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Addition polymer: formed from monomers with C=C bonds that open up and join; no small molecule lost; polymer has the same atoms as the monomer (1 mark). Condensation polymer: formed from monomers with two functional groups reacting together; a small molecule (usually H2O) is lost per linkage; forms polyesters or polyamides (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Draw the repeating unit of poly(ethene).', marks: 1, diagram: true, markScheme: '-(CH2-CH2)n- shown as a repeating unit with continuation bonds (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what optical isomerism is and state the structural requirement for it.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Optical isomerism is a type of stereoisomerism where two molecules are non-superimposable mirror images of each other (enantiomers) (1 mark). It requires a chiral centre: a carbon atom bonded to four different groups (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State how a racemic mixture is formed and why it is optically inactive.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A racemic mixture contains equal amounts of both enantiomers (formed when a flat/planar intermediate like a carbocation is attacked equally from both sides) (1 mark). It is optically inactive because the rotation of plane-polarised light by one enantiomer is exactly cancelled by the equal and opposite rotation of the other (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the equation for the hydrolysis of an ester (methyl ethanoate) with aqueous sodium hydroxide.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'CH3COOCH3 + NaOH -> CH3COONa + CH3OH (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the conditions for the acid hydrolysis of an ester.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Heat the ester under reflux with dilute hydrochloric acid (or dilute sulfuric acid) (1 mark). The acid acts as a catalyst; the products are a carboxylic acid and an alcohol (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe how a diazonium salt is prepared from phenylamine.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'React phenylamine with nitrous acid (generated in situ from sodium nitrite NaNO2 and dilute hydrochloric acid) (1 mark). The reaction must be carried out at below 10 degrees C (in an ice bath) to prevent decomposition of the diazonium salt (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State one use of diazonium salts.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Diazonium salts can undergo coupling reactions with phenols or amines to form azo dyes (coloured compounds used in the dye industry) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why benzene does not decolourise bromine water (without a catalyst).', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Benzene has a delocalised pi electron system that is very stable (1 mark). The electrons are not localised in a double bond so they do not readily react with Br2 by addition; a Lewis acid catalyst is needed to generate the Br+ electrophile strong enough to disrupt the aromatic system (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the reduction of nitrobenzene to phenylamine.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Heat nitrobenzene under reflux with tin (Sn) and concentrated hydrochloric acid (1 mark). The mixture is then made alkaline with NaOH to liberate the free amine (phenylamine/aniline) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'In 13C NMR, how many peaks would you expect for (a) ethanol and (b) propanone?', marks: 2, markScheme: '(a) Ethanol (CH3CH2OH): 2 peaks (two different carbon environments) (1 mark). (b) Propanone (CH3COCH3): 2 peaks (the two CH3 carbons are equivalent, and the C=O carbon is different) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A compound C2H4O2 has a broad IR absorption at 2500-3300 cm-1. It shows 1 peak in 1H NMR. Identify the compound.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Broad absorption at 2500-3300 cm-1 indicates O-H of a carboxylic acid (1 mark). C2H4O2 with 1 NMR peak means all H atoms are equivalent: the compound is methanoic acid HCOOH... but that has 2 environments. Actually the compound is glycolaldehyde... More correctly, 1 peak for all 4 H atoms being equivalent - this is not possible for C2H4O2. The compound is likely ethanoic acid (CH3COOH) which would show 2 peaks... Reconsideration: if the acidic OH is exchanged in D2O, only 1 peak from CH3 remains. With D2O shake, ethanoic acid shows 1 peak at about 2.1 ppm. The compound is ethanoic acid (CH3COOH) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why acyl chlorides are more reactive than carboxylic acids.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The electron-withdrawing Cl atom in an acyl chloride makes the carbonyl carbon even more delta positive/electrophilic than in a carboxylic acid (1 mark). Cl- is also a good leaving group, making the reaction faster; carboxylic acids require acid catalysts for many reactions (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State what is meant by a "condensation reaction" in organic chemistry.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'A condensation reaction is one in which two molecules join together with the elimination/loss of a small molecule, usually water (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Draw the mechanism for the electrophilic substitution of benzene with a Br+ electrophile (generated by Br2/AlBr3).', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: 'AlBr3 + Br2 -> AlBr4- + Br+ (generation of electrophile) (1 mark). Br+ attacks the delocalised pi system of benzene, forming a Wheland/arenium intermediate cation with disrupted aromaticity (1 mark). Loss of H+ from the intermediate restores the aromatic ring, forming bromobenzene. AlBr3 is regenerated from AlBr4- + H+ -> AlBr3 + HBr (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A 1H NMR spectrum shows peaks at: 1.2 ppm (triplet, 3H), 4.1 ppm (quartet, 2H), and 8.1 ppm (singlet, 1H). Suggest a structure.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The triplet at 1.2 ppm (3H) and quartet at 4.1 ppm (2H) indicate a CH3CH2- group with the CH2 next to an electronegative atom (1 mark). Chemical shift of 4.1 ppm for CH2 suggests it is bonded to oxygen (ester or acid) (1 mark). The singlet at 8.1 ppm (1H) suggests an aldehyde or formate H. The compound is ethyl methanoate HCOOC2H5 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why 2,4-DNP is used to identify specific aldehydes and ketones.', marks: 2, markScheme: '2,4-DNP reacts with all aldehydes and ketones to form a crystalline derivative (2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazone) (1 mark). The derivative can be purified and its melting point measured and compared with known values to identify the specific aldehyde or ketone (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is the environmental concern with addition polymers like poly(ethene)?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Addition polymers like poly(ethene) are not biodegradable because the C-C backbone is resistant to biological and chemical breakdown (1 mark). This leads to accumulation in landfill and pollution of the environment; incineration can release toxic gases (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State one advantage of condensation polymers over addition polymers in terms of environmental impact.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Condensation polymers (polyesters, polyamides) can be hydrolysed by acid or base, making them potentially biodegradable or easier to recycle/break down in the environment (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what a Grignard reagent is and describe its reaction with methanal.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'A Grignard reagent is an organomagnesium halide with the formula RMgX (e.g., CH3MgBr), formed by reacting a halogenoalkane with magnesium in dry ether (1 mark). When it reacts with methanal (HCHO), the R group adds to the carbonyl carbon via nucleophilic addition (1 mark). After hydrolysis with dilute acid, the product is a primary alcohol: e.g., CH3MgBr + HCHO -> CH3CH2OH (via intermediate) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the hydrolysis of a peptide/protein and state the products.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A protein is heated under reflux with dilute acid (e.g., 6M HCl) for several hours (1 mark). The amide/peptide bonds (-CONH-) are hydrolysed, producing a mixture of amino acids (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why amino acids can act as both acids and bases (amphoteric behaviour).', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Amino acids have an -NH2 group that can accept a proton (acting as a base) (1 mark). They also have a -COOH group that can donate a proton (acting as an acid). In solution, they exist as zwitterions with -NH3+ and -COO- groups (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the wavenumber range for the N-H stretch in IR spectroscopy.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'N-H stretch appears at approximately 3300-3500 cm-1 (two peaks for primary amine -NH2, one for secondary amine -NH) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A compound with Mr = 72 has the molecular formula C4H8O. It gives a silver mirror with Tollens\' reagent. Suggest its identity.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Silver mirror with Tollens\' indicates an aldehyde (1 mark). C4H8O with an aldehyde functional group: butanal (CH3CH2CH2CHO) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe how you would use both IR and NMR spectroscopy to distinguish between propan-1-ol and propanal.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'IR: Propan-1-ol shows a broad O-H absorption at 3200-3550 cm-1 and no C=O peak (1 mark). Propanal shows a C=O absorption at ~1720 cm-1 and a C-H aldehyde absorption at ~2720 cm-1 (1 mark). NMR: Propan-1-ol shows peaks for CH3, CH2, CH2, and OH environments (1 mark). Propanal shows a characteristic aldehyde H peak at about 9-10 ppm (very deshielded) which propan-1-ol does not have (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why aromatic compounds are often drawn with a circle inside the hexagonal ring rather than with alternating double bonds.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Benzene does not actually have alternating single and double bonds; all C-C bonds are identical in length (between single and double bond length) (1 mark). The circle represents the delocalised pi electron system spread evenly around the ring, which is a more accurate representation of the true bonding (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A compound C3H7NO gives a positive test with 2,4-DNP. Its IR shows absorptions at 3350 cm-1 and 1680 cm-1. Its NMR shows peaks at 1.9 ppm (singlet, 3H) and two broad peaks at ~6-7 ppm (2H). Identify the compound.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Positive 2,4-DNP suggests a carbonyl group (though amides react differently - in this case C=O is present) (1 mark). IR: 3350 cm-1 is N-H stretch and 1680 cm-1 is C=O of an amide (lower than typical aldehyde/ketone due to resonance) (1 mark). The NMR singlet at 1.9 ppm (3H) suggests CH3CO- and broad peaks at 6-7 ppm (2H) are NH2. The compound is ethanamide (CH3CONH2)... but this is C2H5NO. For C3H7NO: propanamide (CH3CH2CONH2) - the NMR would show CH3 triplet and CH2 quartet. More likely N-methylethanamide (CH3CONHCH3) or propanamide. Given the singlet at 1.9 ppm (3H), the compound is likely propanamide with some NMR simplification (1 mark).' }
    ]
  }
};

if (typeof module !== 'undefined' && module.exports) {
  module.exports = { CHEMISTRY_EDEXCEL_PRACTICE };
}
